column1: Who will win the election for Iowa's 3rd Congressional District in 2022?
column5: ['The Democratic Party candidate', 'The Republican Party candidate', 'Someone else']

column6: The prediction markets, poll aggregates, and forecasts are unanimous: this one is red.

Axne (D) is a 2-time incumbent, but it's going to be tough to keep that streak alive against Nunn (R) in this R+3 district given the current circumstances. Even if Republicans weren't surging almost all across the board due to a tried and true script and a well coordinated push from the GOP super PACs, Democrats in tough districts would be in real trouble from the midterm curse alone. As it stands now, some forecasters see this as toss-up, but no one--not the forecasters or the aggregators--are leaning Democrat in this race at the moment, even if it's a close one. The consensus is approximately 60-40 Nunn, and that feels about right.

right now this district across multiple generic polls is listed as lean-republican and/or toss-up; only one specific Axne vs. nunn poll that i could find puts nunn ahead by about 9 points - but still 3 months out from elections
District was won by a hair by D's last time, and Republican candidate seems pretty normal so baseline should be +10 GOP.
current democrat has been elected twice - the first time beating the R incumbent - but might be too close to call - hedging bets on D's maintaining the seat the right
Iowa politics and a rebuke of Biden during a midterm election

This will be a very close race probably decided by who turns out the vote. It is likely that swing voters will be making up their mind right up to the election. My opinion is Republicans have the stronger position on issues but a black swan event can change all projections. My own opinion is that the Republicans have a better chance if Donald Trump is not seen as a likely 2024 presidential candidate. His presence will alienate crucially needed swing voters. This race is likely to react to events right to the close.
Money flowing to Dem candidate and Rep have no coalesced around a single candidate (2/28)
Iowa has been turning more red over the years, but the incumbent is blue. They have been close races though.
IA-3 is a Trump district, and Axne is not a particularly strong incumbent. In a GOP environment, she'll have a tough time hanging on in 2022.
